After the S1 subunit attaches to the cellular receptors, the virus enters the cell through clathrin-mediated endocytosis and is then transported to the early endosomes (
 Inoue et al., 2007). From this point forward, the transmembrane protease serine 2 (TMPRSS2) cleaves the SARS-CoV-2 S protein for a second time and facilitates cell entry and the fusion between the endosomal membrane and the viral S2 sequence (
 Hoffmann et al., 2020b). Consequently, the inhibition of TMPRSS2 could prevent SARS-CoV-2 cellular entry and could play a potential therapeutic role as has been already shown in other viral respiratory syndromes and experimental models (
 Kawase et al., 2012; 
 Yamamoto et al., 2016; 
 Hoffmann et al., 2020b).
